Online_Sales.csv - This file contains actual order data (point of Sales data) at the transaction level with the below variables

  • CustomerID - Customer unique ID
  • Transaction_ID - Transaction Unique ID
  • Transaction_Date - Date of Transaction
  • Product_SKU - Unique ID for the product
  • Product_Description - Product Description
  • Product_Cateogry - Product Category
  • Quantity - Number of items ordered
  • Avg_Price - Price per one quantity
  • Delivery_Charges - Charges for delivery
  • Coupon_Status - Any discount coupon applied

Data Transformation

Changes must be made under original imports to ensure data is available for further use

In[]:
### Calculating the Gross Revenue per Order
import_online_sales['Gross_Order_Revenue'] = import_online_sales['Avg_Price'] * import_online_sales['Quantity']

### Turning discount coupon values into percentage
import_discount_coupon['Real_Discount_pct'] = import_discount_coupon['Discount_pct']/100

### Setting a multiplier for used coupons
import_online_sales['Coupon_Mult'] = np.where(import_online_sales['Coupon_Status'] == 'Used', 1, 0)

### Setting merge conditions, coupons per category and month number
# Turning 'Transaction_Date' type from object to datetime
import_online_sales['Transaction_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(import_online_sales['Transaction_Date'], format='%m/%d/%Y')

# Adding month number to 'import_online_sales' DF
import_online_sales['Transaction_Month'] = import_online_sales['Transaction_Date'].dt.month

# Adding month number to 'import_discount_coupon' DF
temp_month_dict = {'Jan':'01/01/19',
                   'Feb':'01/02/19',
                   'Mar':'01/03/19',
                   'Apr':'01/04/19',
                   'May':'01/05/19',
                   'Jun':'01/06/19',
                   'Jul':'01/07/19',
                   'Aug':'01/08/19',
                   'Sep':'01/09/19',
                   'Oct':'01/10/19',
                   'Nov':'01/11/19',
                   'Dec':'01/12/19'}

import_discount_coupon['Date'] = import_discount_coupon['Month']
import_discount_coupon['Date'] = import_discount_coupon['Date'].map(temp_month_dict)
import_discount_coupon['Month_Number'] = pd.to_datetime(import_discount_coupon['Date'], format='%d/%m/%y').dt.month

### To calculate revenue, coupons must be correct for all items
# Understanding which 'Product_Category's differ between DFs
set(import_discount_coupon['Product_Category']).symmetric_difference(set(import_online_sales['Product_Category']))

# Searching for asymmetries inside DFs
set(import_online_sales['Product_Category']).intersection(set(import_discount_coupon['Product_Category']).symmetric_difference(set(import_online_sales['Product_Category'])))

set(import_discount_coupon['Product_Category']).intersection(set(import_discount_coupon['Product_Category']).symmetric_difference(set(import_online_sales['Product_Category'])))

# Replacing 'Notebook' value with 'Notebooks & Journals' in Coupons DF 'Product_Category'
import_discount_coupon['Product_Category'] = np.where(import_discount_coupon['Product_Category']=='Notebooks', 'Notebooks & Journals', import_discount_coupon['Product_Category'])

# Replacing ['Backpacks', 'Fun', 'Google', 'More Bags'] values with ['Bags', 'Accessories', 'Drinkware', 'Bags'] in Sales DF 'Product_Category'
for x, y in zip(['Backpacks', 'Fun', 'Google', 'More Bags'], ['Bags', 'Accessories', 'Drinkware', 'Bags']):
    import_online_sales['Product_Category'] = np.where(import_online_sales['Product_Category']==x, y, import_online_sales['Product_Category'])

# Replacing {'Backpacks', 'Fun', 'Google', 'More Bags'} values with with ['Bags', 'Accessories', 'Drinkware', 'Bags'] in Taxes DF 'Product_Category'
for x, y in zip(['Backpacks', 'Fun', 'Google', 'More Bags'], ['Bags', 'Accessories', 'Drinkware', 'Bags']):
    import_tax_amount['Product_Category'] = np.where(import_tax_amount['Product_Category']==x, y, import_tax_amount['Product_Category'])

# Removing duplicated coupons for same category in same month
import_discount_coupon = import_discount_coupon.drop_duplicates(subset=['Month', 'Product_Category', 'Discount_pct'], keep='first')

# Transforming Tax rates into numeric types
import_tax_amount['Tax_Rate'] = pd.to_numeric(import_tax_amount['GST'].str.replace('%', '')) / 100

# Removing duplicated Tax Rates [Accessories 10%, Bags 10%, Bags 18%, Drinkware 10%]
import_tax_amount = import_tax_amount[~((import_tax_amount['Product_Category'] == 'Accessories') & (import_tax_amount['GST'] == '10%'))]
import_tax_amount = import_tax_amount[~((import_tax_amount['Product_Category'] == 'Bags') & (import_tax_amount['GST'] == '10%'))]
import_tax_amount = import_tax_amount[~((import_tax_amount['Product_Category'] == 'Drinkware') & (import_tax_amount['GST'] == '10%'))]
import_tax_amount = import_tax_amount.drop_duplicates()

### MARKETING INSIGHTS
# Transforming Date column into actual datetime type
import_mkting_expenses['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(import_mkting_expenses['Date'], format='%m/%d/%Y')

# Adding a 'Month_Number' column to the data import
import_mkting_expenses['Month_Number'] = import_mkting_expenses['Date'].dt.month

# Adding a 'Total_MKTing_Expense' Column to data import
import_mkting_expenses['Total_MKTing_Expense'] = import_mkting_expenses['Online_Spend'] + import_mkting_expenses['Offline_Spend']

# Turning import_online_sales 'CustomerID' into str type instead of float type
import_online_sales['CustomerID'] = import_online_sales['CustomerID'].astype('object')

# Turning import_customer_info 'CustomerID' into str type instead of float type
import_customer_info['CustomerID'] = import_customer_info['CustomerID'].astype('object')

  2. Who are our most loyal customers?
  3. Who are our most profitable customers?

  5. How much did one-timers paid us?

### 1. Totals Table (gross income, loss in coupons, taxes paid, net income, products sold, orders, marketing expense, customers)

# Adding coupons and taxes data to sales data
sales_w_coupons = pd.merge(left=import_online_sales,
                           right=import_discount_coupon[['Month_Number', 'Product_Category', 'Coupon_Code', 'Real_Discount_pct']],
                           left_on=['Transaction_Month', 'Product_Category'],
                           right_on=['Month_Number', 'Product_Category'],
                           how='left').drop(['Month_Number'], axis=1)

sales_w_taxes = pd.merge(left=sales_w_coupons,
                         right=import_tax_amount,
                         on='Product_Category',
                         how='left').drop('GST', axis=1)

sales_table = pd.merge(left=sales_w_taxes,
                       right=import_customer_info,
                       on='CustomerID',
                       how='left')

sales_table['Real_Order_Revenue'] = (sales_table['Gross_Order_Revenue'] * (1-(sales_table['Coupon_Mult']*
                                                                              sales_table['Real_Discount_pct'])))

sales_table['Real_Discount_Cash'] = sales_table['Gross_Order_Revenue'] - sales_table['Real_Order_Revenue']

sales_table['Transaction_Tax'] = sales_table['Real_Order_Revenue'] * sales_table['Tax_Rate']

sales_table['Net_Order_Income'] = sales_table['Real_Order_Revenue'] - sales_table['Transaction_Tax']

#Calculating totals
totals_dict = {}

totals_dict['Total_Gross_Income'] = round(import_online_sales['Gross_Order_Revenue'].sum(), 2)

totals_dict['Total_Cash_Lost_in_Coupons'] = round(sales_table['Real_Discount_Cash'].sum(), 2)

totals_dict['Total_Taxes_Paid'] = round(sales_table['Transaction_Tax'].sum(), 2)

totals_dict['Total_Orders_Net_Income'] = totals_dict['Total_Gross_Income'] - (totals_dict['Total_Cash_Lost_in_Coupons']
                                                                              + totals_dict['Total_Taxes_Paid'])

totals_dict['Total_Marketing_Expenses'] = import_mkting_expenses['Total_MKTing_Expense'].sum()

totals_dict['Company_Net_Income'] = totals_dict['Total_Gross_Income'] - (totals_dict['Total_Cash_Lost_in_Coupons'] + 
                                                                 totals_dict['Total_Marketing_Expenses'] + 
                                                                 totals_dict['Total_Taxes_Paid'])

totals_dict['Total_Products_Sold'] = sales_table['Quantity'].sum()

totals_dict['Total_Active_Customers'] = import_customer_info['CustomerID'].nunique()

totals_dict['Total_Orders'] = sales_table['Transaction_ID'].nunique()
 
totals_table = pd.DataFrame(totals_dict.items(), columns=['Concept', 'Value'])

totals_table['Pct_of_Gross_Income'] = round(totals_table['Value'] / totals_table.loc[totals_table['Concept']=='Total_Gross_Income', 'Value'].iloc[0], 3)*100

### 2. Evolution of revenue / marketing expenses / coupon expenses / net income
revenue_w_coupn = pd.merge(left=sales_table.groupby('Transaction_Month')['Gross_Order_Revenue'].sum().reset_index(),
                           right=sales_table.groupby('Transaction_Month')['Real_Discount_Cash'].sum().reset_index(),
                           on='Transaction_Month',
                           how='inner')

revenue_w_taxes = pd.merge(left=revenue_w_coupn,
                           right=sales_table.groupby('Transaction_Month')['Transaction_Tax'].sum().reset_index(),
                           on='Transaction_Month',
                           how='inner')

revenue_w_mktin = pd.merge(left=revenue_w_taxes,
                           right=import_mkting_expenses.groupby(by='Month_Number')['Total_MKTing_Expense']
                                                                                  .sum()
                                                                                  .reset_index(),
                           left_on='Transaction_Month',
                           right_on='Month_Number', 
                           how='inner').drop('Month_Number', axis=1)

revenue_w_mktin['Net_Income'] = revenue_w_mktin['Gross_Order_Revenue'] - (revenue_w_mktin['Real_Discount_Cash']
                                                                          + revenue_w_mktin['Transaction_Tax']
                                                                          + revenue_w_mktin['Total_MKTing_Expense'])

plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))

sns.barplot(data=revenue_w_mktin, x='Transaction_Month', y='Gross_Order_Revenue',
            palette='crest_r', label='Gross Revenue')

sns.barplot(data=revenue_w_mktin, x='Transaction_Month', y='Net_Income',
            palette='summer', label='Net Income')

sns.lineplot(data=revenue_w_mktin, x=revenue_w_mktin.index, y='Real_Discount_Cash',
             marker='o', markersize=3, color='#8E13F2', label='Coupon Expense')

sns.lineplot(data=revenue_w_mktin, x=revenue_w_mktin.index, y='Transaction_Tax',
             marker='o', markersize=3, color='#F1880E', label='Tax Expense')

sns.lineplot(data=revenue_w_mktin, x=revenue_w_mktin.index, y='Total_MKTing_Expense',
             marker='o', markersize=3, color='#AA1234', label='Marketing Exp')

plt.title('Evolution of Revenue and Net Income')
plt.xlabel('Month Number')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.ylim(0,550*1000)
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1,1))
plt.show()

### 8. Build a pareto to understand impact of best products by net income
best_selling_prods = sales_table.groupby(by='Product_Description')['Net_Order_Income'].sum().reset_index().sort_values(by='Net_Order_Income',
                                                                                                                       ascending=False)
best_selling_prods['Pct_of_Net_Income'] = round(best_selling_prods['Net_Order_Income'] /
                                                best_selling_prods['Net_Order_Income'].sum(),5)

best_selling_prods['Net_Income_Cummulative_Pct'] = best_selling_prods['Pct_of_Net_Income'].cumsum()

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(data=best_selling_prods.head(20),
            x='Product_Description',
            y='Net_Order_Income',
            palette='summer')
plt.xlabel('')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.ylabel('Net Income')
plt.grid(False)

plt.twinx()

sns.lineplot(data=best_selling_prods.head(20),
             x='Product_Description',
             y='Net_Income_Cummulative_Pct',
             marker='o',
             markersize=4,
             color='purple',
             label='Cummulative Percentage\nof Net Income')
plt.title('Net Income per Product Pareto')
plt.ylabel('')
plt.legend(loc='center right')

plt.show()

Business Recommendations

  1. Identify Which products tend to sell together

  2. Classify customers (Detail classification method)

Recommendation 1. Identify Which products tend to sell together

Definitions:

  • Antecedents: Refers to the items that are already present in the basket before a purchase is made.

  • Consequents: Consequents are the items that are likely to be added to the basket based on the presence of certain antecedents.

  • Antecedent Support: Antecedent support is the proportion of transactions in the dataset that contain the antecedent item

  • Consequent Support: Consequent support is the proportion of transactions in the dataset that contain the consequent item

  • Support: Support is the proportion of transactions in the dataset that contain both the antecedent and consequent itemsets. It measures the frequency of co-occurrence of the items.

  • Confidence: Confidence measures the probability that the consequent item or itemset will be purchased given that the antecedent item or itemset is already in the basket.

  • Lift: Lift indicates the strength of the association between the antecedent and consequent. It measures the ratio of observed support to the expected support if the antecedent and consequent were independent. Lift greater than 1 indicates a positive association, while less than 1 indicates a negative association.

  • Leverage: Leverage measures the difference between the observed frequency of antecedent and consequent co-occurrence and the frequency that would be expected if they were independent. It provides insights into whether the presence of the antecedent and consequent together is significantly higher or lower than what would be expected by chance.

  • Conviction: Conviction measures the dependency of the consequent on the antecedent. It is calculated as the ratio of the expected frequency that the antecedent occurs without the consequent to the observed frequency of it occurring without the consequent. Conviction values greater than 1 indicate dependency.

Recommendation:

There where no strong dependencies found using Market Basket Analysis, however, here are some conclusions derived from the analysis below

  1. 'Nest Cam Indoor Security Camera - USA' and 'Nest Cam Outdoor Security Camera - USA' appear together in more than 2% of the company sales,. Also they present a 'Lift' value of 1.66 meaning they are bouhgt together more often with intention rather than pure chance

  2. 'YouTube Custom Decals' and 'Google Laptop and Cell Phone Stickers' seem to have a high 'Lift' value, however, these items don't sell that much, in any case, we can argue that they inspire each others sales

  3. We can also conclude that most 'Nest' products promote the rest of the family products since they appear to be dominating the analysis

Recommendation 2. Classify customers (Detail classification method)

Classifying customers in 'Bronze', 'Silver', 'Platinum' and 'Gold' level

Classification is calulated the following way:

Client 'Total Net Income' percentile MULTIPLIED BY 90%

PLUS Client 'Total Orders' percentile MULTIPLIED BY 10%

  • Bronze Level: Ranging from 0% up-and-equal to 40%

  • Silver Level: Ranging from 40% (Excluding 40%) up-and-equal to 70%

  • Platinum Level: Ranging from 70% (Excluding 70%) up-and-equal to 90%

  • Gold Level: Ranging from 90% (Excluding 90%) up-and-equal to 100%

Recommendation:

Table below show GOLD level customers with NO Orders placed in the Last 90 Days

We recommend to approach these clients if possible

customer_loyalty['Client_Level'] = ((customer_loyalty['Net_Order_Income'].rank(pct=True)*0.80)

                                         bins=[0.00, 0.40, 0.70, 0.90, 1.00],
